Question 2: What is the difference between colspan and rowspan in tables? Provide
examples.
1. colspan
Definition: colspan makes a table cell extend horizontally across multiple columns.
Syntax: <td colspan="number_of_columns">content</td>
Example:
<table border="1">
  <tr>
    <th>Product</th>
    <th colspan="2">Price</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Apple</td>
    <td>100</td>
    <td>USD</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Banana</td>
    <td>50</td>
    <td>USD</td>
  </tr>
</table>

2. rowspan
Definition: rowspan makes a table cell extend vertically across multiple rows.
Syntax: <td rowspan="number_of_rows">content</td>
Example:
<table border="1">
  <tr>
    <th>Category</th>
    <th>Product</th>
    <th>Price</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td rowspan="2">Fruits</td>
    <td>Apple</td>
    <td>100</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Banana</td>
    <td>50</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td rowspan="2">Vegetables</td>
    <td>Tomato</td>
    <td>30</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Potato</td>
    <td>20</td>
  </tr>
</table>

Question 3: Why should tables be used sparingly for layout purposes? What is a better
alternative?
->Tables should be used sparingly for layout purposes because they were originally designed to display tabular data, not to structure the layout of a webpage. Using tables for layout can cause several problems:
->Problems with using tables for layout:
    1.Poor accessibility: Screen readers and other assistive technologies may read table markup as data, confusing users with disabilities.
    2.Less flexible design: Table layouts are rigid and do not adapt well to different screen sizes, making responsive design difficult.
    3.Slower page loading: Tables can create more HTML code and nesting, which slows down page rendering.
    4.Maintenance difficulty: Changing a table-based layout often requires altering multiple rows and columns, which  is cumbersome.
    5.SEO issues: Search engines may misinterpret content structure when tables are misused for layout

->Better alternative:
    The modern approach is to use CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) for layout. CSS provides flexible and semantic ways to structure pages:

Flexbox: Ideal for one-dimensional layouts (rows or columns).
CSS Grid: Powerful for two-dimensional layouts (rows and columns simultaneously).
Positioning and floats: For more specific layout needs, though less preferred tay.

->Example:
Instead of a table for a two-column layout:

<!-- Table layout (bad practice) -->
<table>
  <tr>
    <td>Sidebar</td>
    <td>Main Content</td>
  </tr>
</table>

->Use CSS Grid:
<div class="container">
  <div class="sidebar">Sidebar</div>
  <div class="main">Main Content</div>
</div>

<style>
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 3fr;
  gap: 10px;
}
</style>




